# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eating-animals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eating-animals/2009-in-literature] This article contains information about the literary events and publications of **2009**.
[src:eating-animals/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:eating-animals/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:eating-animals/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:eating-animals/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:eating-animals/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:eating-animals/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:eating-animals/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:eating-animals/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:eating-animals/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:eating-animals/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:eating-animals/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] The book was adapted and extended into a 2018 documentary film with the same name, directed by Christopher Dillon Quinn and co-narrated by Foer and Natalie Portman.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Foer presents the book as a way for him to decide whether or not his newborn child should eat meat.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Foer's son is representative of the generations that are entering a world of industrialized farming, in which the decision to eat meat has many more implications than taste.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] More often than not, putting meat on our plates comes with immense ramifications not only for the animals involved, but also for the environment, and ourselves; the animals suffer, the environment is damaged, and our health is put into question.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Essentially, Foer concludes that the detriments of factory farms outweigh the benefits of taste, which is why he chooses to raise his son a vegetarian.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Throughout the book, Foer places significant emphasis on the stories that come with food.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] To strengthen the emphasis, both the first and the last chapters of the book are entitled “storytelling.” In the book, Foer states that “stories about food are stories about us―our history and our values,” and establishes storytelling as the overriding theme of the whole book.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] For Foer, storytelling is a way of recognizing and dealing with the complexity of the subject that is eating animals, and how it is connected to identity.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] The stories in our plates are the stories about our relationship with the world as represented by the people we eat with, the process by which our food reaches the table, what kinds of food find their ways to our table, etc.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] According to Foer, the way humans cope with and understand complex phenomena is by turning their occurrences into stories about what they mean.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] In this sense, the suggested profundity within the phenomenon of meat eating gives Foer's concept of storytelling a religious undertone.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] As the title suggests, the particular phenomenon Foer focuses on is the consumption of meat.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] He discusses what eating meat has meant in the past, and what it means today.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] In doing so, he does not, as one might expect, make the claim that eating meat is intrinsically bad.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Rather, he claims that eating meat is circumstantially bad; for example, it is bad when it entails the suffering of animals, environmental destruction, and/or a risk for human health.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Today, according to the book and a number of its cited sources, eating meat overwhelmingly entails these problems, while in the past, it has not.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] The conclusion Foer reaches is that eating animals that come from industrial methods―such as factory farming, industrial fishing, and the like―is bad.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Foer notes that most people recognize there is something bad about eating animals, but that people willingly forget this is the case.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Part of what is forgotten in this process, Foer argues, is a connection to our own animality.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] We neglect the parts of us that makes us similar to them―like, for example, the ability to feel or be relieved of pain―and we deny their importance in the constitution of our humanity.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] As Foer puts it, “what we forget about animals, we begin to forget about ourselves.” What this leads to, Foer argues, is a fairly ambiguous sense of shame―the feeling of shame that arises when memory reminds us of what we have willingly forgotten.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Forgetfulness, the book suggests, is reinforced and perpetuated by the lack of transparency in the meat industry.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Farms are generally closed to the public, and it is so difficult to get inside of one that Foer illegally sneaks into one to write about the conditions of the typical factory farm.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] During his operation, he witnesses the dismal conditions in which the animals live, which helps him understand why the industry seeks confidentiality.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] He describes this experience as a direct contrast to the marketing tactics used by factory farms.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] In an attempt to shine light on the meaning of such marketing claims, Foer dedicates a whole chapter to definitions of words that connect humans and food.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] In it, he defines some of the labels and certifications that are assigned to animal products, suggesting that many of them are misleading.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Ultimately, *Eating Animals* discusses the ethics of food.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] It suggests that our food choices directly reflect the ethical values we stand for.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] When people eat meat, Foer claims, they are implying that satisfying their desire for meat is more important than letting animals live well, or even live at all.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] This can be a conscious or unconscious process, but its implications, for Foer, are always real.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] When one supports factory farming, one is relinquishing the importance of certain moral behavior to animals, and in turn, to humans as well.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] For example, if one denies the importance of the suffering of an animal, one denies the importance of the ability to suffer in and of itself, so it follows that one denies the importance of suffering for humans.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] In a similar chain of logic, Foer connects our treatment of animals to our treatment of humans―we dichotomize between those who matter and those who do not.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Consequently, each food choice an individual makes is an ethical one that profoundly impacts both human and non-human animals.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] A *New York Times* best-seller, *Eating Animals* has received mixed reviews from critics.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Some critics praise both the conclusions Foer reaches and how he reaches them.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] According to a piece by the *New Yorker*, the power of the book lies in its ability to discuss why humans can be so loving to their companion animals while simultaneously being completely indifferent to the ones they eat.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Documentary director Christopher Quinn and actress Natalie Portman produced a documentary version of *Eating Animals* in 2018.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] Like the book, the documentary explores the ethics of contemporary animal agriculture.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] The creators hope to expand the reach of *Eating Animals*' message so that more people think of the meat they eat in new ways.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] The film was released in cinemas on June 15, 2018.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film holds an approval rating of 91% based on 46 reviews, with an average rating of 7.00/10.
[src:eating-animals/eating-animals] The site's critics consensus reads: "*Eating Animals*' thoughtful analysis and exploration of corporate farming is impressive, given the scope of the topic." At Metacritic, the film has a weighted average score of 69 out of 100, based on 14 critics, indicating "generally favorable reviews".
